article.headline: Stanley: 'Casino has some kind of luck'
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taj McWilliams-Franklin took the inbounds pass
with 2.4 seconds left. She dribbled twice, making a spin move into
the lane, and powered home a five-foot runner off the glass at the
buzzer to win the game.

"It was an amazing finish," she said.

McWilliams-Franklin's shot gave Connecticut Sun a 65-63 victory
over the Washington Mystics on Tuesday, breaking a two-game losing
streak that included a tough overtime defeat to Detroit on Sunday.

The Mystics figured McWilliams-Franklin would be the fourth
option on a team with Nykesha Sales, Shannon Johnson and Katie
Douglas, but Connecticut coach Mike Thibault wanted his reliable
veteran forward to have the ball for the game-winning play.

"The entire game we didn't run a play to perfection," said
Douglas, who scored a season-high 18 points in her first start
since returning from a foot injury. "But that last play, I think
everybody keyed in. And Taj came up big for us."

The finish spoiled a heroic comeback attempt by Washington's
Coco Miller, who made two 3-pointers in the final 10.3 seconds to
close a six-point deficit and tie the score at 63. Miller scored 13
points to lead the Mystics (2-8), who have lost five straight.

"The casino has some kind of luck," said Washington coach
Marianne Stanley, a reference to the casino where Connecticut plays
its home games.

Johnson also scored 18 points for the Sun (6-5), and Sales broke
out of a game-long slump with two big baskets in the final five
minutes as Connecticut rallied from an eight-point second-half
deficit.

Sales was just 1-for-9 from the field when she hit a 3-pointer
with 4:16 to play to make it 57-55, the Sun's first lead of the
second half. Miller tied the score with a jumper, but Sales hit
another to with 2:40 to go to give Connecticut the lead until
Miller tied it again in the final seconds.

Sales finished with 11 points on 3-for-12 shooting.
McWilliams-Franklin scored eight points.

Mystics leading scorer and rebounder Chamique Holdsclaw sat out
for the fifth time in six games with a strained right hamstring.
Holdsclaw aggravated the injury Friday against Cleveland and is
day-to-day.

Stanley shuffled the lineup, giving rookie Aiysha Smith her
first start and using Stacey Dales-Schuman in a reserve role for
the first time this season.

"I want so badly for them to experience a win right now,"
Stanley said. "At lot of times it takes one win to get a roll
going, and that's what we need. We're a good basketball team that's
struggling."

The Mystics shot only two free throws in the game. Asjha Jones
made them both with 11:05 remaining.
